            <![CDATA[
                    <img src="https://a-slide.github.io/media/posts/7/network2.jpg" alt="" />
                <h3>Dev Style</h3>
<p><span class="md-line md-end-block" ><span class=""><strong>I ❤️ ❤️ ❤️ Python</strong></span> and try to write beautiful and easy-to-maintain code, often using object oriented programming. I sometimes use <span class=""><strong>Cython/C for speed</strong></span>, if multi-threading is not enough. I know my way in R, but thoroughly despise it. I use Bash all the time, though I would never consider it for a script longer than a few lines. Let's face it, it is ugly as hell.</span></p>
<p><span class="md-line md-end-block" >I do all my development on <span class=""><strong>Linux/Ubuntu</strong></span> and my production code runs on a Linux/RedHat <span class=""><strong>high performance computing cluster</strong></span>. I don't really like windows and OSX but since other people do I do my best to write portable multi-platform code. I have experience in <span class=""><strong>GPU computing</strong></span> and <strong>containerisation </strong>and I am getting up to speed in cloud computing as well.</span></p>
<p><span class="md-line md-end-block" > Over the last 7 years I have been actively developing a number of <span class=""><strong>scripts, APIs and analytic workflows for bioinformatic analyses</strong></span>. In particular, I wrote several tools to analyse <span class=""><strong><a spellcheck="false" href="https://nanoporetech.com/">Oxford Nanopore</a> sequencing data</strong></span>, some of which have been gaining popularity in the community</span></p>
<p><a href="https://github.com/a-slide"><img loading="lazy" src="https://github-readme-stats.vercel.app/api?username=a-slide&amp;count_private=true&amp;show_icons=true" data-is-external-image="true"  align="left"></a></p>
